{"title_page": "Bill Gosper", "text_new": "{{short description|American mathematician, programmer/hacker}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name              = Ralph William Gosper Jr.\n| image             = Bill_Gosper_2006.jpg\n| image_size        = 150px\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1943|4|26}} \n| birth_place       = \n| occupation        = Programmer, Computer scientist, Mathematician\n| employer          = \n| residence         = \n| nationality       = American\n| organizations     = [[Xerox PARC]], [[Symbolics]], [[Wolfram Research]], the [[Lawrence Livermore Laboratory]], [[Macsyma, Inc.]]\n| alma_mater        = {{nowrap|[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]}}\n| known_for         = \n}}\n'''Ralph William Gosper Jr.''' (born April 26, 1943), known as '''Bill Gosper''', is an American mathematician and programmer.<ref>[http://www.vintage.org/2007/main/bio.php?id=1379 Bill Gosper] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080110233519/http://www.vintage.org/2007/main/bio.php?id=1379 |date=January 10, 2008 }}, [[Vintage Computer Festival]]. Accessed January 3, 2007.</ref>   Along with [[Richard Greenblatt (programmer)|Richard Greenblatt]], he may be considered to have founded the [[Hacker (programmer subculture)|hacker]] community, and he holds a place of pride in the [[lisp programming language|Lisp]] community.<ref>Levy, Steven, ''[[Hackers: Heroes of the Computer Revolution]]'', (1984)</ref>\n\n==Becoming a hacker==\nIn high school, Gosper was interested in [[model rocket]]s until one of his friends was injured in a rocketry accident and contracted a fatal brain infection.<ref name=\"mmp\">{{citation|contribution=Bill Gosper|title=More Mathematical People|editor1-first=Donald J.|editor1-last=Albers|editor2-first=Gerald L.|editor2-last=Alexanderson|editor2-link=Gerald L. Alexanderson|editor3-first=Constance|editor3-last=Reid|editor3-link=Constance Reid|publisher=Harcourt Brace Jovanovich|year=1990|pages=100\u2013117}}.</ref>  Gosper enrolled in [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] in 1961, and he received his [[bachelor's degree]] in mathematics from MIT in 1965 despite becoming disaffected with the mathematics department because of their anti-computer attitude.<ref name=\"mmp\"/>\n\nIn his second year at MIT, Gosper took a programming course from [[John McCarthy (computer scientist)|John McCarthy]] and became affiliated with the [[MIT AI Lab]].\n\nHis contributions to computational mathematics include [[HAKMEM]] and the MIT [[Maclisp]] system. He made major contributions to [[Macsyma]], [[Project MAC]]'s computer algebra system. Gosper later worked with [[Symbolics]] and [[Macsyma, Inc.]] on commercial versions of Macsyma.\n\nIn 1974, he moved to [[Stanford University]], where he lectured and worked with [[Donald Knuth]].<ref name=\"mmp\"/>\n\nSince that time, he has worked at or consulted for [[Xerox PARC]], [[Symbolics]], [[Wolfram Research]], the [[Lawrence Livermore Laboratory]], and [[Macsyma Inc.]]\n\n==Key contributions==\n\n===Conway's Game of Life===\n{{More citations needed section|date=July 2019}}\nHe became intensely interested in the [[Conway's Game of Life|Game of Life]] shortly after [[John Horton Conway]] had proposed it.  Conway conjectured the existence of infinitely growing patterns, and offered a reward for an example. Gosper was the first to find such a pattern, the [[Gun (cellular automaton)|glider gun]], and won the prize.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Colossal Book of Mathematics |publisher=W. W. Norton |location=New York |author-first=Martin |author-last=Gardner |author-link=Martin Gardner |date=2001 |isbn=0-393-02023-1}}</ref> Gosper was also the originator of the [[Hashlife]] algorithm that can speed up the computation of Life patterns by many orders of magnitude.\n\n===Packing problems===\nGosper has created numerous [[packing problem]] puzzles, such as \"Twubblesome Twelve\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Nested Scrolls: The Autobiography of Rudolf Von Bitter Rucker |author-first=Rudy |author-last=Rucker |author-link=Rudy Rucker |publisher=Macmillan |date=2012 |isbn=978-0-76532753-6 |page=240 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-rbwOWK4Dn8C&pg=PA240}}</ref>\n\n===Symbolic computation===\nGosper was the first person to realize the possibilities of [[symbolic computation]] on a computer as a mathematics research tool,{{cn|date=June 2016}} whereas computer methods were previously limited to purely numerical methods. In particular, this research resulted in his work on [[continued fraction]]<ref name=\"contfrac\">{{cite web |url=https://perl.plover.com/yak/cftalk/INFO/gosper.txt |title=Continued Fraction Arithmetic |author-last=Gosper |author-first=Bill |author-link=Bill Gosper |access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> representations of real numbers and [[Gosper's algorithm]] for finding closed form [[Hypergeometric series|hypergeometric]] identities.\n\nIn 1985, Gosper briefly held the world record for computing the most digits of [[pi#Rapidly convergent series|pi]] with 17 million digits.<ref>{{cite book |author-last1=Arndt |author-first1=J\u00f6rg |author-last2=Haenel |author-first2=Christoph |title=Pi Unleashed |publisher=Springer-Verlag |date=2006 |isbn=978-3-540-66572-4<!--isbn only volume 1--> |url=https://books.google.com/?id=QwwcmweJCDQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |pages=104, 206}} English translation by Catriona and David Lischka. Record was in 1985.</ref> See [[chronology of computation of \u03c0]].\n\n===Space-filling curves===\nIn the continuity of early 20th century examples of [[space-filling curve]]s\u2014the Koch-Peano curve, Ces\u00e0ro and [[L\u00e9vy C curve]], all special cases of the general [[de Rham curve]]\u2014and following the path of [[Benoit Mandelbrot]], Gosper discovered the [[Peano-Gosper curve]], before engaging with variations on the [[Dragon curve|Harter-Heighway dragon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=WqK4ZWbzI6M |title=Plane-Filling Functions vs. Space-Filling Curves |author-last=Gosper |author-first=Bill |author-link=Bill Gosper |access-date=November 1, 2019}}</ref> In the late 80s, Gosper independently discovered the [[Gosper-Lafitte triangle]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Distribution of nonempty triangles inside a fractal rep-4-tile|encyclopedia=The On-Line Encyclopedia of Integer Sequences |date=1995 |url=https://oeis.org/A000360}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Hackers: Heroes of the Computer Revolution]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://gosper.org/ Bill Gosper's webpage] which contains a [http://gosper.org/bill.html Biography]\n*[http://www.tweedledum.com/rwg/ Bill Gosper's Graphics]\n*[http://demonstrations.wolfram.com/TheTroublesomeTwelveCircleProblem/ Twubblesome Twelve] Puzzle - version for the free Mathematica Player\n\n{{Conway's Game of Life}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gosper, Bill}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Number theorists]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Cellular automatists]]\n[[Category:Recreational mathematicians]]\n[[Category:People from Pennsauken Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Lisp people]]\n[[Category:American computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Scientists at PARC]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American mathematician, programmer/hacker}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name              = Ralph William Gosper Jr.\n| image             = Bill_Gosper_2006.jpg\n| image_size        = 150px\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1943|4|26}} \n| birth_place       = \n| occupation        = Programmer, Computer scientist, Mathematician\n| employer          = \n| residence         = \n| nationality       = American\n| organizations     = [[Xerox PARC]], [[Symbolics]], [[Wolfram Research]], the [[Lawrence Livermore Laboratory]], [[Macsyma, Inc.]]\n| alma_mater        = {{nowrap|[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]}}\n| known_for         = \n}}\n'''Ralph William Gosper Jr.''' (born April 26, 1943), known as '''Bill Gosper''', is an American mathematician and programmer.<ref>[http://www.vintage.org/2007/main/bio.php?id=1379 Bill Gosper] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080110233519/http://www.vintage.org/2007/main/bio.php?id=1379 |date=January 10, 2008 }}, [[Vintage Computer Festival]]. Accessed January 3, 2007.</ref>   Along with [[Richard Greenblatt (programmer)|Richard Greenblatt]], he may be considered to have founded the [[Hacker (programmer subculture)|hacker]] community, and he holds a place of pride in the [[lisp programming language|Lisp]] community.<ref>Levy, Steven, ''[[Hackers: Heroes of the Computer Revolution]]'', (1984)</ref>\n\n==Becoming a hacker==\nIn high school, Gosper was interested in [[model rocket]]s until one of his friends was injured in a rocketry accident and contracted a fatal brain infection.<ref name=\"mmp\">{{citation|contribution=Bill Gosper|title=More Mathematical People|editor1-first=Donald J.|editor1-last=Albers|editor2-first=Gerald L.|editor2-last=Alexanderson|editor2-link=Gerald L. Alexanderson|editor3-first=Constance|editor3-last=Reid|editor3-link=Constance Reid|publisher=Harcourt Brace Jovanovich|year=1990|pages=100\u2013117}}.</ref>  Gosper enrolled in [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] in 1961, and he received his [[bachelor's degree]] in mathematics from MIT in 1965 despite becoming disaffected with the mathematics department because of their anti-computer attitude.<ref name=\"mmp\"/>\n\nIn his second year at MIT, Gosper took a programming course from [[John McCarthy (computer scientist)|John McCarthy]] and became affiliated with the [[MIT AI Lab]].\n\nHis contributions to computational mathematics include [[HAKMEM]] and the MIT [[Maclisp]] system. He made major contributions to [[Macsyma]], [[Project MAC]]'s computer algebra system. Gosper later worked with [[Symbolics]] and [[Macsyma, Inc.]] on commercial versions of Macsyma.\n\nIn 1974, he moved to [[Stanford University]], where he lectured and worked with [[Donald Knuth]].<ref name=\"mmp\"/>\n\nSince that time, he has worked at or consulted for [[Xerox PARC]], [[Symbolics]], [[Wolfram Research]], the [[Lawrence Livermore Laboratory]], and [[Macsyma Inc.]]\n\n==Key contributions==\n\n===Conway's Game of Life===\n{{More citations needed section|date=July 2019}}\nHe became intensely interested in the [[Conway's Game of Life|Game of Life]] shortly after [[John Horton Conway]] had proposed it.  Conway conjectured the existence of infinitely growing patterns, and offered a reward for an example. Gosper was the first to find such a pattern, the [[Gun (cellular automaton)|glider gun]], and won the prize.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Colossal Book of Mathematics |publisher=W. W. Norton |location=New York |author-first=Martin |author-last=Gardner |author-link=Martin Gardner |date=2001 |isbn=0-393-02023-1}}</ref> Gosper was also the originator of the [[Hashlife]] algorithm that can speed up the computation of Life patterns by many orders of magnitude.\n\n===Packing problems===\nGosper has created numerous [[packing problem]] puzzles, such as \"Twubblesome Twelve\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Nested Scrolls: The Autobiography of Rudolf Von Bitter Rucker |author-first=Rudy |author-last=Rucker |author-link=Rudy Rucker |publisher=Macmillan |date=2012 |isbn=978-0-76532753-6 |page=240 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-rbwOWK4Dn8C&pg=PA240}}</ref>\n\n===Symbolic computation===\nGosper was the first person to realize the possibilities of [[symbolic computation]] on a computer as a mathematics research tool,{{cn|date=June 2016}} whereas computer methods were previously limited to purely numerical methods. In particular, this research resulted in his work on [[continued fraction]]<ref name=\"contfrac\">{{cite web |url=https://perl.plover.com/yak/cftalk/INFO/gosper.txt |title=Continued Fraction Arithmetic |author-last=Gosper |author-first=Bill |author-link=Bill Gosper |access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> representations of real numbers and [[Gosper's algorithm]] for finding closed form [[Hypergeometric series|hypergeometric]] identities.\n\nIn 1985 Gosper briefly held the world record for computing the most digits of [[pi#Rapidly convergent series|pi]] with 17 million digits.<ref>{{cite book |author-last1=Arndt |author-first1=J\u00f6rg |author-last2=Haenel |author-first2=Christoph |title=Pi Unleashed |publisher=Springer-Verlag |date=2006 |isbn=978-3-540-66572-4<!--isbn only volume 1--> |url=https://books.google.com/?id=QwwcmweJCDQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |pages=104, 206}} English translation by Catriona and David Lischka. Record was in 1985.</ref> See [[chronology of computation of \u03c0]].\n\n===Space-filling curves===\nIn the continuity of early 20th century examples of [[space-filling curve]]s\u2014the Koch-Peano curve, Ces\u00e0ro and [[L\u00e9vy C curve]], all special cases of the general [[de Rham curve]]\u2014and following the path of [[Benoit Mandelbrot]], Gosper discovered the [[Peano-Gosper curve]], before engaging with variations on the [[Dragon curve|Harter-Heighway dragon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=WqK4ZWbzI6M |title=Plane-Filling Functions vs. Space-Filling Curves |author-last=Gosper |author-first=Bill |author-link=Bill Gosper |access-date=November 1, 2019}}</ref> In the late 80s, Gosper independently discovered the [[Gosper-Lafitte triangle]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Distribution of nonempty triangles inside a fractal rep-4-tile|encyclopedia=The On-Line Encyclopedia of Integer Sequences |date=1995 |url=https://oeis.org/A000360}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Hackers: Heroes of the Computer Revolution]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://gosper.org/ Bill Gosper's webpage] which contains a [http://gosper.org/bill.html Biography]\n*[http://www.tweedledum.com/rwg/ Bill Go